@misc{Hughes1996,
abstract = {We describe three new techniques to track fish swimming movements in 3-D, in either still or flowing water. The first technique uses two or more video cameras to track a single point in 3-D. This method is more general, simpler, more flexible, and more precise than the widely used stereo method. Its use of a 3-D calibration quadrat frees the investigator to arrange cameras and adjust zoom lenses as he or she pleases, in contrast with the rather stringent requirements of the stereo method. It also allows a simple one-step rectification of all sources of systematic errosrs such as perspective effects, refraction at the air-water interface, and spherical distortion by the lens. the second technique expands the first to allow tracking of the fish's midline in 3-D. This simplifies tracking of the fish's center of mass and should facilitate the application of models that describe how swimming thrust is produced by a fish's body movements. The third technique allows estimation of swimming speed for fish foraging in flowing water, where there is significant velocity shear, permitting more accurate estimates of energy expenditure.},
